{"parse":{"title":"Ramayana Centre","pageid":8722247,"revid":835601675,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>Ramayana Centre</b> is cultural and spiritual organization based in <a href=\"/wiki/Port_Louis\" title=\"Port Louis\">Port Louis</a>, Mauritius. It was founded in 2001 by an act passed in the <a href=\"/wiki/National_Assembly_of_Mauritius\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"National Assembly of Mauritius\">National Assembly</a> of the Republic of <a href=\"/wiki/Mauritius\" title=\"Mauritius\">Mauritius</a> to promote and propagate the Hindu epic <i><a href=\"/wiki/Ramayana\" title=\"Ramayana\">Ramayana</a></i> and the spiritual, social and cultural values flowing therefrom.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hindu_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hindu-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Prior to this, no parliament of any country had enacted a Bill or set up an institution for the dissemination of the perennial values of the Ramayana.\n</p><p>The Bill was unanimously approved on May 22, 2001 and was proclaimed as an Act by the President of the Republic on June 14, 2001. It was published in the <i>Government Gazette</i> No. 64 on June 30, 2001.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The president of the Ramayana Centre is Pandit Rajendra Arun, scholar of the Ramayana and author of several books on various characters of the Ramayana. In 2002, on  Tulsi Jayanti day, the foundation stone of the Ramayana Center laid by Prime Minister, Anerood Jugnauth. <sup id=\"cite_ref-hindu_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hindu-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Subsequently the building of formally inaugurated in 2007  by the then Prime Minister Dr. Navinchandra Ramgoolam. <sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ramayana_Centre&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-hindu-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-hindu_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-hindu_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.hinduismtoday.com/blogs-news/hindu-press-international/ramayana-center-in-mauritius/2305.html\">\"Ramayana Center in Mauritius\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Hinduism_Today\" title=\"Hinduism Today\">Hinduism Today</a> Magazine</i>. August 15, 2002<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2015-09-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Hinduism+Today+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=Ramayana+Center+in+Mauritius&amp;rft.date=2002-08-15&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hinduismtoday.com%2Fblogs-news%2Fhindu-press-international%2Framayana-center-in-mauritius%2F2305.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARamayana+Centre\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://mauritiustimes.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=3308%3Arng-ramayana-centre&amp;Itemid=54\">\"Ramayana Centre\"</a>. <i>Mauritius Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\